If a $4$-foot by $8$-foot rectangular piece of plywood will be cut into $4$ congruent rectangles with no wood left over and no wood lost due to the cuts, then each piece will have dimensions $a \times b,$ where $a$ and $b$ are positive real numbers such that $4a = 8b.$  Hence, $a = 2b.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.8 cm);

draw((0,0)--(8,0)--(8,4)--(0,4)--cycle);

label("$8$", (4,0), S);
label("$4$", (0,2), W);

label("$a$", (0.8,0.4));
label("$b$", (4,2.4));
[/asy]

The area of each piece is then $ab = 2b^2,$ so $b = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} a.$  Then $a = 2b = 2/\sqrt{2} \cdot b,$ so $b = \frac{2}{3}.$  Then $a = \frac{4}{3}.$

The greatest perimeter is achieved when the rectangle is $2/3 \times 2,$ and the least perimeter is achieved when the rectangle is $1 \times 1/3.$  The positive difference between these perimeters is $2 \left( \frac{4}{3} + 2 \cdot \frac{2}{3} \right) - 2 \left( 1 + 2 \cdot \frac{1}{3} \right) = \boxed{\frac{8}{3}}.$

